[[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer - here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 South African government statements]\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/media/ NICD media]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 WHO Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Official government website for information about Coronavirus in South Africa]\n*[https://t.me/CoronaZABot Corona Telegram Bot for South Africa]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "RoastPrune7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Updated death count)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Josh Lillis", "text_new": "{{short description|English footballer}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Josh Lillis\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Joshua Mark Lillis<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/efl-documents/efl-professional-retain-list--free-transfers---2017-18.pdf |format=PDF |page=62|title=EFL Released and Retained List 2017-18 |publisher=English Football League |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|6|24|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/josh-lillis-42145/|title=Josh Lillis |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.89|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/teams/first-team/goalkeeper/josh-lillis/ |title=Josh Lillis |publisher=Rochdale A.F.C. |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]\n| clubnumber = 1\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132004\n| youthclubs1 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| caps1 = 39\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2009\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 5\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2009\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 4\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2009\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 1\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 23\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2012\u2013\n| clubs6 = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]\n| caps6 = 228\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs7 = [[A.F.C. Fylde|Fylde]] (loan)\n| caps7 = 3\n| goals7 = 0\n| club-update = 18:53, 3 April 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Joshua Mark Lillis''' (born 24 June 1987) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[A.F.C. Fylde|Fylde]], on loan from [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] in the [[Football League One|League One]] and [[Football League Championship|Championship]]. He spent time on loan at [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], and [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], before making a permanent move to former loan club [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] in 2012.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\nBorn in [[Derby]], [[Derbyshire]], Lillis worked his way through [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]'s youth system, and made his d\u00e9but as a professional at [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 22 December 2006. He spent most of his time at the Iron as the understudy of [[Joe Murphy (footballer born 1981)|Joe Murphy]], but has improved under the coaching of former [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] stalwart [[Kevin Pressman]].\n\nIn January 2009, Lillis went to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on a one-month loan in order to experience more first team action. He made his d\u00e9but in 2\u20132 draw with [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] on 20 January 2009. His first clean sheet for the Magpies came on 14 February where Notts County beat [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] 2\u20130. He returned to Scunthorpe making 5 appearances and 1 clean sheet.\n\nOn 1 September 2009, he signed for [[Grimsby Town]] on loan as cover for injured [[Nick Colgan]]. He made his d\u00e9but on 5 September 2009 against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]], in a 4\u20130 defeat. He made four appearance before returning to the Iron. On 30 October he joined [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] on an emergency seven-day loan. His d\u00e9but was in a 4\u20130 win over [[AFC Bournemouth]] on 31 October 2009.\n\nIn July 2010, he was loaned to Rochdale again for six months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/r/rochdale/8793268.stm|title=Rochdale sign Scunthorpe United goalkeeper Josh Lillis|date=6 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nLillis returned to Scunthorpe at the end of his loan spell, but found his chances limited at Glanford Park and was released in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18018280|title=Cliff Byrne heads Scunthorpe United departures|date=10 May 2012|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Rochdale===\nOn 12 June 2012, [[Rochdale A.F.C|Rochdale]] announced that he had signed a two-year deal to return to Spotland where he had previously had a successful loan spell. After impressive displays in Rochdale's 2013/14 promotion campaign, Lillis has since committed himself to Rochdale for a further two years.\n\nOn 26 May 2016, Lillis signed a new two-year deal with Rochdale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochdaleafc.co.uk/news/article/josh-lillis-signs-new-contract-3126893.aspx?|title=Josh Lillis Signs New Dale Contract|date=26 May 2016|publisher=Rochdale AFC|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nLillis joined [[A.F.C. Fylde|Fylde]] on loan until the end of the season on 6 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.afcfylde.co.uk/josh-lillis-joins-the-coasters/ |title=Josh Lillis Joins The Coasters! |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=A.F.C. Fylde |language=en-GB |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nHe is the son of former [[Scunthorpe United]] player and assistant manager [[Mark Lillis]].\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 14 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!